<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Tax policy making process</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">FBA0011/13-14</span></p><h2 style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">HMRC/HMT—Written evidence</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Tax Policy Making: A New Approach</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In June 2010 the Government committed to improve the way in which tax policy is developed, communicated and legislated, and published a consultation document: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Tax policy-making: a new approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. In December 2010 the Government published </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The new approach to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> tax policy making: a response to the consultation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, which set out details of the new tax policy making process. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">During the Tax Policy Making consultation, officials met more than 40 tax practitioners to discuss the way we make tax policy: including lawy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ers, accountants, and tax managers and received over 40 written responses.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Following consultation, the Government announced five major changes which have a substantial impact on the way tax policy is made and communicated: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5.3pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">• Where the Government is emba</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rking on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">major areas of tax </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reform</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, it will set out its policy objectives and rationale for reform, building on the approach taken in the Corporate Tax Road Map. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5.3pt 36pt"><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">• Tax policies will be developed over a </span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">longer policy cycle</span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The majority of tax measures will be announced at Budgets for inclusion in the Finance Bill the following year at the earliest. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5.25pt 36pt"><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">• The Government will use the period between the Budget and the following Finance Bill to consult on proposed policy changes </span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and draft legislation. The Government published a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Tax Consultation Framework</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that outlines its approach to consultation on tax policy and </span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">legislation. In summary, the framework commits to:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5.25pt 100.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">consulting earlier on tax policy, tailoring the approach to cons</span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ultation to suit the circumstances; and </span></li><li style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">publishing</span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> more legislation in draft, and in particular publishing the majority of Finance Bill clauses in draft, for greater scrutiny, at least 3 months before introduction of the Bill. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">• The Government will ta</span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ke a </span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">more strategic approach</span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tax </span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">avoidance, and its response to significant avoidance risks will be balanced with improving predictability and stability in the tax system. The Government published a </span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Protocol</span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">setting out the circumstances in which it wil</span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l announce legislative changes with immediate effect outside fiscal events. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">• </span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">When announcing changes to tax law, the Government will ensure that it clearly sets out what the change is</span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="color:#2d2d2d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> why it is being proposed and what impact it will have. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Evaluation of the tax policy making process</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Tax Professionals Forum</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Forum of Tax Professionals was announced in July 2010 by the Exchequer Secretary to oversee improvements to the framework for developing tax policy and making tax law.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Forum was es</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tablished to ensure that the Government is held to account in the development of tax policy through greater scrutiny, transparency and evaluation. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Forum also has a role in providing advice and guidance about whether the Government’s stated principles </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and this new approach are being followed in practice. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Forum meets bi-annually, and the remit and membership is reviewed every two years. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Details are available at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">https://www.gov.uk/government/policy-advisory-groups/tax-professionals-forum</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Forum ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s published two independent annual reports on the implementation of the new tax policy making process: </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/204924/taxprofessionalforum_270313.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">27 March 20</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">1</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">3</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/204925/taxprofessionalforum_061211.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">6 December 2011</span></a></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Government is continuing to engage with the Forum on areas where, on occasion due to concerns regarding avoidance, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it has not been able to follow the full stages of the new approach.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Office of Tax Simplification</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">With a commitment to simplifying the tax system, the Government established the Office for Tax Simplification (OTS) in July 2010.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The work of the OTS has already led to some significant simplification reforms. Following the OTS’s review of reliefs, the Government has abolished over 40 obsolete and little-used tax reliefs, removing c. 90 pages of legislation. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Finance Bill </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Government has conducted around 30 formal and informal consultations on tax changes announced at Budget 2013. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Government published 15 consultation response documents on 10 December 2013. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Around 133 clauses/over 300 pages of draft legislation was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">published on 10 December 2013 for technical consultation. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Government welcomes comments to ensure that legislation works as intended and the technical consultation period that began on 10 December 2013, will be open for 8 weeks, closing on 4 February 2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">014. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:left;"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UNCLASSIFIED</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>